, put out a report this week declaring that we=E2=80=99re in the third act =
of the streaming wars=E2=80=94an era defined by industry consolidation and =
more spending on live sports rights by traditional media companies and stre=
amers. =E2=80=9CFrom the leagues=E2=80=99 perspectives, there is a delicate=
 balance between reach (e.g., NFL on broadcast TV) and immediate money (e.g=
=2E, MLS on Apple TV),=E2=80=9D Nathanson
wrote, neatly summing up the philosophy that guided the NBA=E2=80=99s media=
 rights auction. =E2=80=9CIn order to stay relevant and grow the game, it i=
s in the best interest of sports leagues to maximize eyeballs.=E2=80=9D<br/=
><br/>Streamers have different strategies when it comes to sports programmi=
ng=E2=80=94Amazon wants broadcast-style packages, Apple wants to own everyt=
hing, and Netflix wants to focus on unique events. But they=E2=80=99ve all =
shown a willingness to invest in sports rights=E2=80=94even Netflix, which =
is paying around $150 million for two NFL games on Christmas Day. As reader=
s of The Varsity know well, legacy media companies see live sports as their=
 last chance to save the lucrative cable bundle, setting up a competition f=
or sports rights which Nathanson believes will increasingly be dominated by=
 the streamers. =E2=80=9CGoing forward, as technology improves and latency =
comes down, streaming will become a more suitable home for sports than it i=
s today,=E2=80=9D he wrote. =E2=80=9CIn addition, games/matches from
smaller leagues may start to pop up on sports betting apps, but there isn=
=E2=80=99t an expectation that betting operators will be the primary rights=
 holders for top-tier leagues anytime soon.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/></li><li><i>D=
isney=E2=80=99s legal drama</i>: Sports media newshounds have been focused =
on the Sunday Ticket case. But there=E2=80=99s another class-action suit ma=
king its way through U.S. District Court in San Francisco that has the pote=
ntial to upend the way we watch=E2=80=94and pay for=E2=80=94sports. The sui=
t alleges that Disney used ESPN, Hulu, and =E2=80=9Cmost-favored nations=E2=
=80=9D clauses in contracts essentially to raise rates for live sports. Ear=
lier this week, Judge <b>Edward Davila </b>ruled against Disney=E2=80=99s b=
id to get the lawsuit tossed. (Funnily enough, the ruling cites the Sunday =
Ticket case as precedent.)<br/><br/>I asked Eriq to explain the judge=E2=80=
=99s decision. =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s set aside the headline that this spec=
ific lawsuit survives dismissal and moves forward. (Disney can rightfully c=
laim certain
victories, such as knocking out the plaintiffs=E2=80=99 hope for damages un=
der federal antitrust law.) What=E2=80=99s important here is the growing ch=
allenge Disney faces in maintaining its position as a streaming bundler=E2=
=80=94whether through Hulu With Live TV or through the upcoming Venu=E2=80=
=94while also serving as a major sports programmer via ESPN for other distr=
ibutors like DirecTV and YouTube TV. Any advantages Disney reserves for its=
elf will face intense scrutiny, and the marketplace benefits are going to n=
eed to outweigh the drawbacks. We can expect more of this analysis in separ=
ate legal challenges toward Venu.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/></li><li><i>Adios, Seth=
 Waugh</i>: As soon as word got out late yesterday that <b>Seth Waugh</b> w=
as stepping down as C.E.O. of PGA of America, I started calling around in s=
earch of the <i>real</i> story. It turns out that there is no other story. =
After spending six years heading up the organization, the well-liked Waugh =
decided not to renew his deal. The PGA gig was
a second career for Waugh, formerly C.E.O. of Deutsche Bank Americas. =E2=
=80=9CIt was inevitable that he was going to run it for a certain period of=
 time and move on,=E2=80=9D a source told me. <br/><br/><b>Kerry Haigh</b>,=
 the group=E2=80=99s chief championships officer, will serve as interim C.E=
=2EO. Meanwhile, C.O.O. <b>Craig Kessle=
r</b>, who joined the organization las=
t year after a five-year stint with Topgolf, is considered a strong possibi=
lity to replace Waugh, whose main accomplishment was cutting long-term TV d=
eals for the PGA Championship (with CBS) and the Ryder Cup (with NBC) that =
run into the next decade. He=E2=80=99s also been given kudos for relocating=
 the group=E2=80=99s headquarters from Florida to Frisco, Texas.</li><br/><=
li><i>Happy trails</i>: It=E2=80=99s the end of an era over at <i>Broadcast=
ing+Cable</i> and <i>Multichannel News</i>, where <b>Kent Gibbons </b>is <u=
><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2Ukt=
xclJLZ0dRWEhiRk1CZXlEREdMU3psQmNpRT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmV4dHR2Lm=
